<div id="review_1044602883" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1044602883" />
    <a title="Sam Benson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34598252-sam-benson"><img alt="Sam Benson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1420161261p2/34598252.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1044602883?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sam Benson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sam Benson" href="/user/show/34598252-sam-benson">Sam Benson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1044602883" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16161602655444796001">I don&apos;t know...this book really is funny at times, and he has a very engrossing (if at times somewhat exhaustive) way of describing the southwest landscape; however, it&apos;s really just too long and rambling and boring for me. Plus, I wasn&apos;t quite sure what to do with the casual racism and sexism that&apos;s sprinkled throughout the book. I know Abbey was a satirist, so perhaps there is an element of satire involved in pointing out the racism of the white characters on both sides of the conflict (the de</span>
  <span id="freeText16161602655444796001" style="display:none">I don't know...this book really is funny at times, and he has a very engrossing (if at times somewhat exhaustive) way of describing the southwest landscape; however, it's really just too long and rambling and boring for me. Plus, I wasn't quite sure what to do with the casual racism and sexism that's sprinkled throughout the book. I know Abbey was a satirist, so perhaps there is an element of satire involved in pointing out the racism of the white characters on both sides of the conflict (the developers/capitalists and the eco-anarchists). But it wasn't overtly critiqued either. So that's troublesome.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16161602655444796001" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

